<!-------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<hr> 
<b><font color="#800080"> 18th Febuary: </font></b>
<b>Mike Hogg</b> (Southampton - GR) 
<p>
<b>Fish, Bathtubs and Black holes </b>
<p>
We look at the possibility of exploring properties of Black Hole physics in a laboratory. We concentrate on the use of super-fluid vortices as an analogue for a Kerr Black Hole.
&nbsp;
<p>
<A HREF="Mike_Hogg_apgr_02_2013.pdf">
[download talk]
</A>


<!-------------------------------------------------------------------------------->
<hr> 
<b><font color="#800080"> 11th Febuary </font></b>
<b>Justin Lovegrove</b> (Southampton - Applied)
<p>
<b>Reverberation mapping in quasars  </b>
<p>
Quasars are highly luminous galactic nuclei, so distant that
they cannot be resolved as anything more than a point with current generations
of telescopes.  I will discuss how reverberation mapping, a form of 'echo-location'
using the light emitted by the central luminous object, may have given
us an unprecedented insight into the finer structure of quasars. 
<p>
We will also have an introductory talk from Marta Colleoni on QFT.
&nbsp;
<p>
<A HREF="Justin_Lovegrove_apgr_02_2013.ppt">
[download talk]
</A>


